Generates the C++ golden-test header that pins the C++ dictionary to the Rust reference walker's behavior. For each sampled stroke sequence, it emits the walker's rendered text and validity (terminal match or not), which the `javelin-ext` unit test replays through the generated dictionary to verify C++-vs-walker agreement. The header is test input only, never consulted by lookups.

`emit_test_header(types, constructs) -> Result<String, ExpandError>` collects sampled sequences via `sample_sequences`, generates a `uint32_t` stroke-mask array for each sequence via `mask_array`, and builds a `GenGolden` struct array via `golden_row`, wrapping it in a fixed C++ preamble. `mask_array` encodes each stroke to a 6-digit hex mask; `golden_row` walks the sequence through `walk()` to get text and validity, then formats a struct initializer with C-escaped text. Unmatched sequences carry empty text and `valid=false`; non-terminal matches carry bracket-stripped in-progress text from `display_text()` and `valid=true`. The stroke-mask format (6-digit hex, `0x` prefix, `u` suffix) must match the C++ struct's field type `uint32_t`; the text escaping via `c_escape()` must match C string literal rules.